Defendant in custody.
The defendant is sentenced to the Wisconsin State Prison system for a total of five and one half (5.5) years.  That is eighteen (18) months initial confinement followed by four (4) years extended supervision.
The defendant has credit for 498 days.
The defendant is found eligible for both the Challenge Incarceration Program and the Substance Abuse Program.
Conditions of extended supervision:
1) Pay court costs;
2) pay supervision fees in an amount to be determined by DOC;
3) assessment, treatment, counseling as deemed appropriate by the Departments assessment process;
4) AODA assessment and follow through;
5) Maintain absolute sobriety;
6) Defendant is to use only one doctor to prescribe medications and only one pharmacist to dispense medications unless approved by the agent;
7) No association with any know drug dealers or users;
8) Maintain fulltime employment, schooling or combination.
Minutes.

Defendant in custody.
On count 1, the State moves to delete the penalty enhancer of within 1000 feet of a school.  Motion granted.
Attorney LaBre presents a letter to the Court dated 08-05-14 and requests that it be sealed in the file.
The Court reads the letter and orders it to be sealed.
NO CONTEST plea entered to the amended charge of deliver heroin in count 1. Convicted.
The State moves to dismiss and read in count 2. Motion granted.
Sentence Withheld.  Defendant is placed on probation to DOC for three (3) years.
Conditions of probation:
1) Spend eight (8) months in the county jail, under the Huber Law, commencing immediately;
2) AODA assessment and follow through;
3) Submit to random urine screens and pay for same;
4) Maintain fulltime employment, schooling or combination;
5) Pay $240.00 to Metro Drug for buy money, joint and several with Logan Daly;
6) Assessment, treatment, counseling as deemed appropriate by the Departments assessment process;
7) pay supervision fees in an amount to be determined by DOC;
8) no association with any known drug dealers or users.
Court costs are waived.
If revoked, the parties stipulate that the defendant has credit for 183 days.  (04-21-14 to today)
